com.versant.fund
Interface ClassHandle

All Superinterfaces:
Handle, SelectBuilder
public interface ClassHandle
extends Handle, SelectBuilder

A specialized Handle used only for handles to database class objects. Database operations that act on a specific class in a specific database tend to live here.

Method Detail

makeObject

Handle makeObject()
Create an instance of this class, create a cached object descriptor for the new object, allocate space for the new object in the object cache and returns a handle to the new object.

The new object is created in the same database as the class object. Use locateClass() or defineClass() to get the class object from a particular database and then pass that class object to makeObject().

The new object is not pinned in memory.

Attribute values are initially set to null. You can use put() on Handle to set the attribute values.

See Also:
ClassBuilder.defineClass(String), Session.locateClass(String)

createIndex

void createIndex(java.lang.String attrname,
                 int indextype)
Create an index on an attribute of this class.

Options for indextype are:

  • Constants.BTREE_INDEX: B-tree.
  • Constants.HASH_INDEX: Hash table.
  • Constants.UNIQUE_BTREE_INDEX: Unique B-tree index.
  • Constants.UNIQUE_HASH_INDEX: Unique hash table.
Indexes can improve query performance, but they are not necessary to perform a query.

Indexes do not have names.

An attribute can have up to two indexes, one a B-tree index (normal or unique) and the other a hash table index (normal or unique).

The actual creation of indexes does not occur until the current short transaction is committed.

A unique index prevents instances of a class from having duplicate values in the designated attribute. Attribute values are checked when a commit or query flushes objects. If a duplicate value is found, you get the error SM_E_SAMEKEYFOUND. If a class has duplicate values in an attribute and you try to create a unique index on that attribute, you get the error SM_E_DUPLICATEKEY.

Once an attribute has an index of a particular kind (either b-tree or hash), you cannot change its uniqueness. If you try to do so, you get the error SCH_INDEX_CONFLICT. Instead, you must delete the existing index and then create a new one.

Parameters:
attrname - the name of attribute on which the index is to be built.
indextype - the type of index to create.

deleteIndex

void deleteIndex(java.lang.String attrname,
                 int indextype)
Drop an index of type indextype for an attribute attrname of this class.

Options for indextype are:

  • Constants.BTREE_INDEX: B-tree.
  • Constants.HASH_INDEX: Hash table.
  • Constants.UNIQUE_BTREE_INDEX: Unique B-tree index.
  • Constants.UNIQUE_HASH_INDEX: Unique hash table.

To delete a B-tree index, you can use either BTREE_INDEX or UNIQUE_BTREE_INDEX. To delete a hash table index, you can use either HASH_INDEX or UNIQUE_HASH_INDEX.

Indexes do not have names.

You must be connected to the database containing the index.

Parameters:
attrname - the name of the attribute.
indextype - the index type of the attribute.
See Also:
ClassHandle.createIndex(String,int)

renameAttr

void renameAttr(java.lang.String oldname,
                java.lang.String newname)
Change the name of an attribute in this class.

The name is changed from attrname to newname. The new name must be unique to the class. The class may be a leaf or non-leaf class. The change occurs in the source database for this class object. Changes are not propagated to subclasses.

Parameters:
oldname - the current attribute name.
newname - the new attribute name.

insertAttrsAt

void insertAttrsAt(AttrBuilder[] newAttrs,
                   int position)
Add the new attributes specified in newAttrs to this leaf or non-leaf class in its source database, beginning after the position specified as position.

To insert at the beginning, specify position as 0.

Before the new attributes are added, a write lock is placed on the class object. Afterwards, the class object is marked dirty.

The newAttrs parameter is a fixed array of new attributes built by newAttrType() methods on Session.

Parameters:
newAttrs - the new attributes to insert.
position - the location before the insertion point for the new attribute.
See Also:
ClassHandle.appendAttr(AttrBuilder), ClassBuilder.defineClass(String), Session.locateClass(String), Session.newAttrBuilder(Attr)

synchronizeClass

void synchronizeClass(java.lang.String targetDb,
                      int option)
Synchronizes the definition of this class in the database targetdb using the class definition in the source database.

Alternatives for option are:

  • Constants.SC_ABORT: If the classes have differing definitions, make no changes and returns SCH_CLSDEF_CONFLICT to the error number variable.
  • Constants.SC_DROP_INSTS: Drop the class and all instances in the target database and create a new class using the class definition in the source database.
  • Constants.SC_PRESERVE_INSTS: Do not drop instances even if changes are necessary.

The receiver ClassHandle object must be a leaf class.

If the class does not exist in the target database, it is created using the definition in the source database.

If an error occurs, you must rollback the transaction in order to keep the databases in a consistent state.

Parameters:
targetDb - database whose class definition is to be changed.
option - synchronization options.
